==English==
===Noun===
'''clout''' (''plural'' clouts)
# A [[cloth]]; a piece of cloth or leather; a patch; a rag.
# A swadding cloth.
# A piece; a fragment. [Obs.]
# The center of the [[butt]] at which [[archer]]s shoot; -- probably once a piece of white cloth or a nail head.
# An iron plate on an [[axletree]] or other wood to keep it from wearing; a [[washer]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1866''': Clouts were thin and flat pieces of iron, used it appears to strengthen the box of the wheel; perhaps also for nailing on such other parts of the cart as were particularly exposed to wear. &mdash; James Edwin Thorold Rogers, ''A History of Agriculture and Prices in England'', Volume 1, p. 546.
# A blow with the hand. [Low]
====Derived terms====
'''clout-nail'''
:a kind of wrought-iron nail heaving a large flat head; -- used for fastening clouts to axletrees, plowshares, etc., also for studding timber, and for various purposes.
:'''Quotations'''
:*'''1866''': They must have been light, for, reckoned by the hundred, the average is not very different from that of the hundred-weight of iron; and clout-nails must have been of moderate size, as the value varies very little from that of horseshoe-nails. &mdash; James Edwin Thorold Rogers, ''A History of Agriculture and Prices in England'', Volume 1, p. 546.